WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.320
It's great seeing everyone.

00:00:05.320 --> 00:00:10.720
The goal is to give you all the opportunity to learn a little bit about data science leadership

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:16.000
from an accomplished data science leader each week and from each other.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.280
We virtually have no agenda, so please ask questions.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:25.120
We'll start with a few light topics just to get things going.

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:26.320
Don't be shy.

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:30.920
Turn on your video camera, introduce yourself in the chat, ask some questions.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:34.279
We have people monitoring the chat, so we'll get to your question if you ask.

00:00:34.279 --> 00:00:39.400
All that said, I am so happy to introduce this week's expert.

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:44.080
He's not exactly a stranger to rstudio and no shortage of impressive things about him.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:48.279
Jonathan, why don't you introduce yourself and tell everyone what you're working on and

00:00:48.279 --> 00:00:49.279
your background.

00:00:49.279 --> 00:00:50.279
Sure.

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:51.279
Thank you.

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:54.360
Thanks for having me, Rob, and rstudio.

00:00:54.360 --> 00:00:56.639
Thank you for having me back.

00:00:56.639 --> 00:00:58.759
My name is Jonathan Regenstein.

00:00:58.759 --> 00:01:05.180
I'm currently the head of data and quantum mental research at Truist Securities within

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:06.839
equity research.

00:01:06.839 --> 00:01:13.639
And before that, I worked at rstudio for a little over four years as our director of

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:14.720
financial services.

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:20.199
So really, really good to be back and to see some familiar faces again.

00:01:20.199 --> 00:01:25.320
And I can give a little background on what we actually do, which is a question we get

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:26.320
asked a lot.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:29.239
I'm sure a lot of data science teams do.

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:33.959
We're a pretty new team within Truist Securities.

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:39.919
And if the name Truist doesn't sound familiar, we used to be called SunTrust and BB&T.

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:48.120
And then those two banks merged together to form one big bank called Truist, which I don't

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:52.599
think is a real word, but it is now.

00:01:52.599 --> 00:01:55.160
So that's who we are.

00:01:55.160 --> 00:02:01.639
And yeah, so we're formally called the data science and engineering team.

00:02:01.639 --> 00:02:10.559
And our job really is to bring what we call, and this is a pretty savvy crowd, so maybe

00:02:10.559 --> 00:02:16.720
I don't need to use these buzzwords, but we say we're bringing modern data science tooling

00:02:17.039 --> 00:02:18.520
to the world of equity research.

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:25.960
So equity research has existed at Truist for a long time, probably 30 years.

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:31.520
And basically, it's market research at the sector level, at the individual ticker level.

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:36.479
So people making recommendations on various stocks, making recommendations on sectors

00:02:36.479 --> 00:02:38.639
and market moves.

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:46.479
And so we have about 35 experts who have been doing this for a long time, but they've kind

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:52.520
of traditionally lived in the world of Excel spreadsheets and Excel models and traditional

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:54.399
market data.

00:02:54.399 --> 00:03:00.919
And the goal of our team is to try to bring modern data science tooling, so things like

00:03:00.919 --> 00:03:07.240
R and RStudio, but also tools like AWS and Snowflake, which haven't traditionally been

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:09.160
used at the bank.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:11.880
So there's kind of a tooling aspect to what we do.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:13.919
There's a data aspect to what we do.

00:03:13.919 --> 00:03:22.639
So the word of alternative data has become very hot in the financial world, which is

00:03:22.639 --> 00:03:27.720
really just data that's not traditional financial and market data.

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:36.320
So you can think of NLP-based data or things like app downloads, something we work on a

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:42.679
lot is just taking our internal banking data, like credit card data, and just mining those

00:03:42.679 --> 00:03:45.000
for insights about the markets.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.839
So that's kind of our role, is to take modern data science tooling, take alternative sources

00:03:49.839 --> 00:03:57.279
of data, and bring all that stuff to the traditional research process, which has been rolling along

00:03:57.279 --> 00:04:02.720
really well for the last, I don't know, call it 30 years, but we're just trying to kind

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:07.960
of bring new processes and new ways of doing things and kind of augment what's already

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:13.039
been a really strong business for the bank.

00:04:13.039 --> 00:04:21.640
Something pretty, some pretty, some sources of both excitement, but also sometimes difficulty

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:29.359
is that we're kind of the first data science team to arrive in our business line.

00:04:29.359 --> 00:04:33.679
So the good thing is, we get to be the tip of the sphere on a ton of the cool stuff that

00:04:33.679 --> 00:04:35.000
we're working on.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.040
I mean, just AWS, right?

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:40.839
No one was using AWS before we got here.

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:45.559
I mean, let alone putting RStudio Server and Connect on AWS.

00:04:45.559 --> 00:04:48.359
So that was a far cry.

00:04:48.359 --> 00:04:54.519
So we get to kind of pioneer all that stuff and bring these new practices, but at the

00:04:54.519 --> 00:05:02.119
same time, sometimes the pioneers don't survive that journey.

00:05:02.119 --> 00:05:05.320
So we're constantly fighting the pioneers fight too.

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:09.359
We're saying we want to do things differently and it takes a lot of time.

00:05:09.359 --> 00:05:13.839
So we get to work on really cool stuff, but then we also have to overcome a lot of just

00:05:13.839 --> 00:05:19.000
the kind of inertia of the way things have always been done in the past.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.399
So it's pretty fun.

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:27.559
It's a really good challenge that we get to take on and yeah, it's been really exciting.

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:33.279
I mean, another really cool thing about being kind of the first data science team to land

00:05:33.279 --> 00:05:38.559
here is that we really started with a green field in terms of our coding stack.

00:05:38.559 --> 00:05:44.279
So we didn't have to come kind of have debates about Python and Julia and R.

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:52.399
We just kind of said, we're going to start with R first and RStudio first, honestly,

00:05:52.399 --> 00:05:53.640
and just kind of go from there.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:06:00.480
So that was another kind of lucky thing that we had from being, again, the first data science

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:07.920
team, but no shortage of conversations we've had to have about, well, I mean, hey, what

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:08.920
is R?

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:09.920
Okay.

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:10.920
We've had that conversation many times.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:12.359
What are these packages?

00:06:12.359 --> 00:06:13.359
What is CRAN?

00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:14.440
Where are these lessons coming from?

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:15.440
Okay.

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:16.440
How do you manage your packages?

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:17.440
Is there a package manager?

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:25.200
And we say, yes, RStudio has a package manager, okay, let's go examine what that is.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:26.640
Why can't y'all just use Tableau?

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:31.839
We've had that conversation a million times of why we prefer to use Shiny.

00:06:31.839 --> 00:06:40.160
So we've been just digging and digging and digging and really trying to bring workflows

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:42.279
into the way that we want to be doing them.

00:06:42.399 --> 00:06:48.480
I mean, we've even started using, frankly, R Markdown for almost all of our reporting

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:53.440
and just getting the templates to look and feel the way people wanted the templates to

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:54.440
look and feel.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:07:00.279
I mean, that in itself took quite a bit of time because everything needs to kind of flow

00:07:00.279 --> 00:07:08.600
into everything needs to be in the right format to just get into our corporate template manager.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:11.679
So we've just been slowly taking on these battles.

00:07:11.679 --> 00:07:18.079
And then of course, trying to add value along the way, which is always the most important

00:07:18.079 --> 00:07:20.440
thing for us.

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:21.920
So those can be small things.

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:28.600
Those can be, when I say small things that can mean like providing data that's clean,

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:34.480
that can be really valuable to a team that isn't used to cleaning data.

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:37.320
It could be, you know, running models and trying to put together some forecasts for

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:38.320
people.

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:41.720
So doing the kind of cooler data science-y type stuff.

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:44.839
But you know, we've definitely learned a win is a win.

00:07:44.839 --> 00:07:50.040
So if it's going to be a simple win from cleaning data, we go for it.

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:54.959
It's going to be a more complex win from, you know, trying to do some forecasting.

00:07:54.959 --> 00:07:57.600
We'll go for that too.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:07:59.079
I see a lot of stuff coming in that I haven't really...

00:07:59.079 --> 00:08:01.119
Yeah, it looks like the questions are coming in.

00:08:01.359 --> 00:08:09.079
Could you maybe just give everyone a sense of the size of the team that you lead?

00:08:09.079 --> 00:08:12.040
And maybe just a quick note on the makeup of it.

00:08:12.040 --> 00:08:13.040
Yeah.

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:14.040
So we're a pretty small team.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:16.239
There's four of us right now.

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:24.200
So one member of the team is just, he's not officially called a data engineer.

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:25.679
It's really funny.

00:08:25.679 --> 00:08:29.239
We don't have that title at the bank.

00:08:29.239 --> 00:08:30.700
It doesn't exist.

00:08:31.279 --> 00:08:35.580
So I think he's just called like a research associate, but functionally, he's really a

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:37.780
data engineer.

00:08:37.780 --> 00:08:45.059
So he does a lot of like data harvesting, you know, web scraping, cleaning, getting

00:08:45.059 --> 00:08:50.979
stuff into databases, just the way we need to be able to access them.

00:08:50.979 --> 00:08:54.659
And then there's kind of two, I guess you could just call them more traditional data

00:08:54.659 --> 00:09:02.859
scientists, in addition to myself, who are of varying degrees of seniority.

00:09:02.859 --> 00:09:04.940
One of them is just recently out of college.

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:08.900
The other one has been out for quite a while.

00:09:08.900 --> 00:09:14.940
And within Truist, we have something called the Data Science Accelerator Program, which

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:20.619
I didn't know it existed until I got here.

00:09:20.619 --> 00:09:24.419
But this teammate went through our Data Science Accelerator Program, which is, it's actually

00:09:24.419 --> 00:09:25.419
a pretty cool program.

00:09:25.419 --> 00:09:26.940
We can talk about it later.

00:09:26.940 --> 00:09:31.659
I had nothing to do with instituting it, so I can dispassionately say it's a really good

00:09:31.659 --> 00:09:32.659
program.

00:09:32.659 --> 00:09:40.739
It's like an 18-month, basically, rotational program where people, you know, apply as if

00:09:40.739 --> 00:09:46.099
it's going to be a full-time job at the bank, but instead of just choosing a job, they enter

00:09:46.099 --> 00:09:51.260
the Data Science Accelerator, which is really a chance to do three six-month rotations around

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:55.419
different parts of the bank, and learn different skills, and just meet different people, see

00:09:55.419 --> 00:09:57.659
different business lines along the way.

00:09:57.659 --> 00:10:00.260
So that's where one of our teammates came from.

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:05.619
I think I blanked on, was there a second part of your question, Rob?

00:10:05.619 --> 00:10:06.619
I know that was a big make-up.

00:10:06.619 --> 00:10:07.619
No, no, that's good.

00:10:07.619 --> 00:10:09.820
And we have plenty of questions to get to anyway.

00:10:09.820 --> 00:10:13.580
The first one that came in, right, if we're going to do this diplomatically, the first

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:15.659
one that came in was from Sep.

00:10:15.659 --> 00:10:19.340
And Sep, I don't know if you're comfortable introducing yourself and asking your question.

00:10:19.419 --> 00:10:24.140
I'll take silence as I'll ask the question for you, but I'll give you a chance to ask

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:25.140
your question.

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:27.140
Yeah, no, not a problem.

00:10:27.140 --> 00:10:28.140
Hi, everybody.

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:29.140
My name is Sep.

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:32.140
I work at Concert AI, a real-world data company.

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:36.140
Yeah, I think, nice to meet you, Jonathan.

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:38.140
Appreciate you sharing all that background.

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:44.140
I think, certainly, perhaps you triggered a lot of people when you were discussing some

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:50.940
of the hesitancy that other groups that maybe are kind of clinging on to some of this legacy

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:52.940
process or legacy technology.

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:58.940
So, my question for you, or maybe if you don't mind sharing some of your strategies for kind

00:10:58.940 --> 00:11:01.940
of working with that and maybe overcoming some of that.

00:11:01.940 --> 00:11:03.940
Yeah, definitely.

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:05.940
And it's definitely ongoing.

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:11.940
So, I don't want to give the impression that we've got it all sorted out.

00:11:12.739 --> 00:11:19.739
So, I mean, for better or worse, I mean, step one was really finding, like, a really good

00:11:19.739 --> 00:11:25.739
partner within the IT org who really, you know, wanted to work with us and was really

00:11:25.739 --> 00:11:31.739
invested in what we were doing and in our success because that's kind of the person

00:11:31.739 --> 00:11:33.739
that communicates upstream.

00:11:33.739 --> 00:11:35.739
Not right now.

00:11:35.739 --> 00:11:37.739
Yeah, you look good.

00:11:37.739 --> 00:11:39.739
You look great.

00:11:40.539 --> 00:11:44.539
So, yeah, that was definitely a really important step one.

00:11:44.539 --> 00:11:48.539
And we have, we talk to that person at least once a week.

00:11:48.539 --> 00:11:51.539
Usually it ends up being two or three times a week.

00:11:51.539 --> 00:11:56.539
It's just like a, I don't know, it's been a really important, valuable relationship

00:11:56.539 --> 00:12:02.539
that, I mean, now it's been, you know, over a year that we've been working together.

00:12:02.539 --> 00:12:09.539
And, you know, he wasn't one of those teammates that I kind of referenced, but he's a really

00:12:09.539 --> 00:12:11.539
important part of the team.

00:12:11.539 --> 00:12:16.539
So, that was huge because he kind of helps us communicate the value proposition.

00:12:16.539 --> 00:12:28.539
And then the second part of that, I guess, was really, like, trying to get small wins

00:12:28.539 --> 00:12:31.539
along the way and frequently.

00:12:31.539 --> 00:12:35.539
So, like I was saying, we'll take small victories.

00:12:35.539 --> 00:12:40.539
We don't hold out for when we have to, you know, change the world with a new piece of

00:12:40.539 --> 00:12:42.539
data science.

00:12:42.539 --> 00:12:51.539
If we can use AWS to, like, really quickly deliver data to people, you know, that's a

00:12:51.539 --> 00:12:53.539
big win for us.

00:12:53.539 --> 00:12:58.539
Especially, like, we'll put Shiny on top of it and we can make data accessible to 20 people.

00:12:58.539 --> 00:13:00.539
And people get that.

00:13:00.539 --> 00:13:02.539
That really resonates.

00:13:02.539 --> 00:13:06.539
So, like, simple things that resonate with people have been really, really helpful for us,

00:13:06.539 --> 00:13:08.539
too.

00:13:08.539 --> 00:13:12.539
But, I mean, it sounds so crazy to say this in the world of data science, but relationship

00:13:12.539 --> 00:13:14.539
building was, like, critical.

00:13:14.539 --> 00:13:16.539
Just critical to what we did.

00:13:16.539 --> 00:13:19.539
Especially at a bank, you know, we're a really big company.

00:13:19.539 --> 00:13:21.539
Thousands of people.

00:13:21.539 --> 00:13:24.539
Thousands of requests for new technology.

00:13:25.539 --> 00:13:32.539
You know, there's no way to avoid going through all the security scans and check marks that we

00:13:32.539 --> 00:13:34.539
have to go through.

00:13:34.539 --> 00:13:38.539
So, you know, we just want to make sure we have a good partner who's going to help us do

00:13:38.539 --> 00:13:40.539
that.

00:13:40.539 --> 00:13:42.539
And, like I said, I mean, it's still ongoing.

00:13:42.539 --> 00:13:47.539
Like, we're constantly having those conversations and refining things.

00:13:47.539 --> 00:13:52.539
But also, I mean, I'll even take a step even further back than that.

00:13:52.539 --> 00:13:58.539
This is probably more relevant, you know, for people who are starting something and new.

00:13:58.539 --> 00:14:04.539
But it was something I really asked before I even came over here, which is just really make

00:14:04.539 --> 00:14:10.539
sure that, like, senior leadership was bought into what we were trying to do.

00:14:10.539 --> 00:14:12.539
That was really, really important.

00:14:12.539 --> 00:14:20.539
Because when push has come to shove on a few things, we've had to really just kind of go ask

00:14:20.539 --> 00:14:24.539
someone really senior to say, we just need this push through.

00:14:24.539 --> 00:14:26.539
And we always explain why.

00:14:26.539 --> 00:14:28.539
But sometimes we just kind of need a push through.

00:14:28.539 --> 00:14:32.539
So I guess that comes back to relationships, too, but it's a little different from the everyday

00:14:32.539 --> 00:14:38.539
weekly relationship we have with our IT or I guess you could really call them functionally our

00:14:38.539 --> 00:14:40.539
DevOps team.

00:14:40.539 --> 00:14:45.539
So, yeah, you know, showing value up the chain has been really important for us, too.

00:14:45.539 --> 00:14:51.539
And, I mean, I don't want to I should also say, you know, our leadership was already kind of

00:14:51.539 --> 00:14:56.539
invested and supportive of this, which is why we're here in the first place.

00:14:56.539 --> 00:14:59.539
So I think that's important also, honestly.

00:14:59.539 --> 00:15:05.539
Like, you know, to the extent that anyone can control this and you can't always, but it's

00:15:05.539 --> 00:15:11.539
always good to be either at an organization or in a part of the organization where the senior

00:15:11.539 --> 00:15:16.539
leadership is really supportive of data science and what we're doing.

00:15:16.539 --> 00:15:19.539
So that's been, yeah, that's been really huge.

00:15:19.539 --> 00:15:20.539
Thank you.

00:15:20.539 --> 00:15:22.539
Yeah, for sure.

00:15:22.539 --> 00:15:26.539
All right, Daniel, are you there?

00:15:26.539 --> 00:15:27.539
Yes, I'm good.

00:15:27.539 --> 00:15:28.539
Can you hear me okay?

00:15:28.539 --> 00:15:29.539
Yeah, yeah.

00:15:29.539 --> 00:15:31.539
Why don't you introduce yourself and ask your question?

00:15:31.539 --> 00:15:32.539
Sure, sure, sure.

00:15:33.539 --> 00:15:35.539
So I'm Daniel, obviously.

00:15:35.539 --> 00:15:41.539
I'm a lead data scientist at Nestle, so likewise a large corporation.

00:15:41.539 --> 00:15:49.539
And we've had some form of statistics statisticians for almost as long as Nestle has been a company.

00:15:49.539 --> 00:15:55.539
But in the more recent past, I would say in the past two to three years, we're trying to

00:15:56.539 --> 00:16:03.539
modernize, do I guess what you would call more standard data science work streams.

00:16:03.539 --> 00:16:08.539
So that includes hiring folks with new different skills, myself included.

00:16:08.539 --> 00:16:14.539
And so my question, which you spoke to a little bit about earlier, but is really kind of thinking

00:16:14.539 --> 00:16:21.539
about, we tend to have many more people that are more statistically minded.

00:16:21.539 --> 00:16:27.539
They can do programming, but they're less adept at kind of doing the productionalization steps

00:16:27.539 --> 00:16:32.539
necessary to get something kind of end to end.

00:16:32.539 --> 00:16:38.539
And so just thinking about if it makes more sense to kind of upskill the folks we have

00:16:38.539 --> 00:16:43.539
to kind of have people that can kind of take things end to end, or to have really a smaller

00:16:43.539 --> 00:16:49.539
number of specialized people with maybe more knowledge on just that final piece of getting

00:16:50.539 --> 00:16:53.539
something through to production.

00:16:53.539 --> 00:16:55.539
Yeah, that's a really good question.

00:16:55.539 --> 00:16:59.539
It's something we have been thinking about a lot.

00:16:59.539 --> 00:17:06.540
We haven't honestly quite got to the point that we're quote unquote putting things into

00:17:06.540 --> 00:17:11.540
production, though we have had to go through a lot of the process for having our production

00:17:11.540 --> 00:17:13.540
environment set up.

00:17:14.540 --> 00:17:19.540
But we've kind of been down a similar journey just for a lot of the things we've been doing.

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:26.540
